#a[1a]

#bl[Clinical importance of taking drug history of a patient]

#bl[Identify drug-related cause of current illness]

- NSAIDs → gastritis, peptic ulcer, GI bleeding
- ACE inhibitors → chronic cough
- Steroids → diabetes, hypertension
- Anticoagulants (warfarin) → bleeding
- Aminoglycosides → nephrotoxicity

#bl[Detect drug interactions]

- Warfarin + antibiotics → ↑ bleeding
- Nitrates + sildenafil → severe hypotension
- Rifampicin → reduced efficacy of OCPs

#bl[Prevent prescribing errors]

- Avoid contraindicated drugs (e.g. metformin in renal failure)
- Avoid duplication within same class
- Identify previous drug allergy (e.g. penicillin → anaphylaxis)

#bl[Assess compliance and treatment failure]

- Poor BP/diabetes control due to non-adherence
- Irregular use of inhalers in asthma

#bl[Guide safe management and monitoring]

- Dose adjustment in renal/hepatic impairment
- Monitoring required (e.g. insulin, warfarin, digoxin)
- Enquire about OTC drugs, herbal remedies, alcohol use


#a[Answer to Question No.: 1b]


#bl[Information obtained from examination of the pulse]

#bl[Rate]

- Tachycardia (e.g. fever, shock, hyperthyroidism)
- Bradycardia (e.g. heart block, hypothyroidism, drugs – β-blockers)

#bl[Rhythm]


- Regular
- Irregularly irregular → atrial fibrillation
- Regularly irregular → ectopic beats
#bl[Volume (amplitude)]

- Low volume/thready → shock, heart failure
- High volume/bounding → fever, anemia, aortic - regurgitation

#bl[Character (contour)]

- Slow rising (anacrotic) → aortic stenosis
- Collapsing pulse → aortic regurgitation
- Pulsus paradoxus → cardiac tamponade, severe asthma
- Pulsus alternans → left ventricular failure
#bl[Condition of vessel wall]

- Thickened, tortuous → atherosclerosis

#bl[Equality and radio-radial/radio-femoral delay]

- Unequal pulses → arterial obstruction
- Radio-femoral delay → coarctation of aorta


#a[2a]
_Probable diagnosis: Acute Myocardial Infarction - STEMI/NSTEMI_

#bl[Investigations with expected findings]


#bl[12-lead ECG]

- ST elevation in ≥2 contiguous leads → STEMI
- ST depression / T wave inversion → NSTEMI/unstable angina
- Pathological Q waves (later)

#bl[Cardiac biomarkers]

- Troponin I/T → elevated (most specific)
- CK-MB → elevated (rises within 4–6 hrs)

#bl[Blood tests]

- FBC (baseline)
- Blood glucose (often elevated)
- Renal function & electrolytes (before ACEI/contrast)
- Lipid profile

#bl[Chest X-ray]

- Cardiomegaly
- Pulmonary edema (if LV failure)

#bl[2D Echocardiography]

- Regional wall motion abnormalities
- Reduced ejection fraction

#bl[Coronary angiography]

- Coronary artery occlusion (definitive)

#a[2.b]

#bl[Treatment of MI after 4 hours]

#bl[Immediate Management]

_Admitted to ICU_
- Aspirin 300 mg chewed
- Clopidogrel 300 mg chewed
- Oxygen (if SpO2 < 90%)
- Nitroglycerin (sublingual, if not hypotensive)
- Morphine for Severe pain

#bl[Since, >2 hours but < 6 hours]

if anterior MI, 
- PCI

#bl[Since, < 12 hours]
- Thrombolytics
  
#bl[If NSTEMI]
- Anoxaparin(Low Molecular Weight Heparin)
